Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}(thinly sliced). Peel and mince or grate half the @garlic{1%clove}.

Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. (Save potatoes for another use.)

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @oil{}, half the @fry seasoning{1%tablespoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until browned and crispy, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Swap in broccoli for potatoes; roast 12-15 minutes.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add onion; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> If onion begins to brown too quickly, add a splash of water.

Stir in @balsamic vinegar{5%teaspoon} and @sugar{1%teaspoon}. Continue cooking until onion is caramelized and jammy, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat; transfer to a #small bowl{}. Wash out pan.

In a second #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} with a pinch of garlic (taste and add more from there if desired). Season with salt and pepper.

Form @ground beef{10%ounce} into two patties, each slightly wider than a burger bun. Season all over with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for onion over medium-high heat. Add patties; cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

In the last 1-2 minutes of cooking, top each patty with @Monterey Jack cheese{1/2%cup}; cover pan to melt cheese.

Halve @potato buns{2} and toast until golden. Spread cut sides of buns with @ketchup{1%unit} and garlic mayo to taste. Fill with patties and as much onion jam as you like. Serve with potato wedges on the side.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.